## At Esalen, men got the PBS specials while women got $12.50 per massage

The gender dynamics at Esalen Institute map the same pattern onto a different axis. The institute's founding mythology centers on men doing intellectual work — **Michael Murphy** and **Dick Price** (both Stanford-educated) co-founding the institute, **Fritz Perls** running encounter groups, **Abraham Maslow** providing the philosophical framework of self-actualization, **Alan Watts** translating Eastern philosophy, **Joseph Campbell** teaching mythology, **Stanislav Grof** developing transpersonal psychology, **Gregory Bateson** bringing systems theory. These men got book deals, PBS specials, professorships, named academic chairs, and enduring cultural legacies.

The women who made Esalen what it actually *is* — the place people go to be touched, moved, and physically transformed — worked for hourly wages. **Peggy Horan** arrived in 1969, co-created Esalen Massage with Deborah Medow, Brita Ostrom, and Vicki Topp, managed the Healing Arts department for a decade, founded the Esalen Massage School, and after more than 50 years is classified as a "legacy teacher." She recalls: **"Massages cost $15 at the time, of which we got $12.50."** No residuals, no royalties, no platform that outlasts the hour of physical contact.

The economic arithmetic is devastating. Campbell's *The Power of Myth* PBS series (1988) became one of the most watched in public television history. The companion book, edited by Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, was a national bestseller. His earlier *Hero with a Thousand Faces* directly shaped George Lucas's *Star Wars* — a franchise worth tens of billions. Alan Watts wrote 25 books and had a TV series; his lectures now have hundreds of millions of YouTube views, generating ongoing revenue managed by his son. **Intellectual work generates residual income: royalties compound for decades after death. Bodywork generates only hourly income — when you stop touching, you stop earning.** The work leaves no tangible product.

Two women's stories expose the structural mechanism most clearly. **Charlotte Selver** (1901–2003) led the very first experimental workshop at Esalen in 1963 — before Perls, before anyone else. Her Sensory Awareness work directly influenced Perls, Erich Fromm, and Alan Watts. She held a faculty position at the New School for Social Research. Yet she has no PBS special, no bestselling book, no named chair. Her husband Charles Brooks wrote the book about her method. **Ida Rolf** (1896–1979) held a PhD in biochemistry from Columbia — earned in 1920, making her one of the most credentialed people at Esalen by far. She worked at the Rockefeller Institute. Yet she is remembered as a bodyworker, and her systematic intellectual work was reduced to the colloquialism "Rolfing" — a nickname she disliked. Meanwhile, male intellectuals retained the formal framing of their contributions: "Gestalt therapy," "humanistic psychology," "comparative mythology."

Jeffrey Kripal's 594-page *Esalen: America and the Religion of No Religion* (2007), the definitive institutional history, reproduces the hierarchy it could have analyzed. Multiple reviewers note the absence of critical gender analysis and the overwhelming focus on male thinkers. The book's index is dominated by male names. The very act of writing the history recapitulates the pattern: "real" history is about ideas (male); the body (female) is backdrop.

